FAQs
Is it expensive to study medicine in Warsaw?

Tuition fees in Warsaw vary depending on the university and program. On average, international students can expect to pay between €8,000 and €15,000 per year for medical programs at the Medical University of Warsaw. Additionally, living costs, including accommodation, food, and transportation, can range from €6,000 to €10,000 per year.
Do I need to speak Polish to study medicine in Warsaw?

While Polish is the official language, many universities, including the Medical University of Warsaw, offer medical programs taught in English for international students. Proficiency in Polish is not typically required for admission to these programs, though learning some basic Polish can enhance your experience and help you navigate daily life more easily.
Are there scholarship opportunities for international students in Warsaw?

Yes, there are various scholarship opportunities for international students in Warsaw. Both the Polish government and the Medical University of Warsaw offer scholarships based on academic merit, financial need, and other criteria. These scholarships can significantly reduce the cost of tuition and living expenses, making it more affordable to study medicine in Warsaw.
With this comprehensive guide, you can embark on an exciting journey to study medicine in Warsaw at the Medical University of Warsaw and achieve your academic and career goals.
